SIMPLE: obturator
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obturator
<hw>Ob"tu*ra`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L.
<ets>obturare</ets> to stop up: cf. F. <ets>obturateur</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>That which closes or stops an opening.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>An apparatus designed to close an
unnatural opening, as a fissure of the palate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Ordnance)</fld> <def>Any device for preventing the
escape of gas through the breech mechanism of a breech-loading gun; a
gas check.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Photog.)</fld> <def>A camera shutter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obturator</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Obturator
<hw>Ob"tu*ra`tor</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Serving as
an obturator; closing an opening; pertaining to, or in the region of,
the obturator foramen; <as>as, the <ex>obturator</ex>
nerve</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Obturator foramen</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>an
opening situated between the public and ischial parts of the innominate
bone and closed by the <xex>obturator membrane</xex>; the thyroid
foramen.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obtusangular</ent>⟦br⟧
